01539 /*
01540  * this must be before the system/machine includes, to allow them to
01541  * override and turn off inlining. To do so, they should do the
01542  * following:
01543  *
01544  *    #undef NETSNMP_ENABLE_INLINE
01545  *    #define NETSNMP_ENABLE_INLINE 0
01546  *
01547  * A user having problems with their compiler can also turn off
01548  * the use of inline by defining NETSNMP_NO_INLINE via their cflags:
01549  *
01550  *    -DNETSNMP_NO_INLINE
01551  *
01552  * Header and source files should only test against NETSNMP_USE_INLINE:
01553  *
01554  *   #ifdef NETSNMP_USE_INLINE
01555  *   NETSNMP_INLINE function(int parm) { return parm -1; }
01556  *   #endif
01557  *
01558  * Functions which should be static, regardless of whether or not inline
01559  * is available or enabled should use the NETSNMP_STATIC_INLINE macro,
01560  * like so:
01561  *
01562  *    NETSNMP_STATIC_INLINE function(int parm) { return parm -1; }
01563  *
01564  * NOT like this:
01565  *
01566  *    static NETSNMP_INLINE function(int parm) { return parm -1; }
01567  *
01568  */
01569 /* #undef NETSNMP_BROKEN_INLINE */
01570 #ifdef NETSNMP_BROKEN_INLINE

01572 #else
01573 #   define NETSNMP_ENABLE_INLINE 1
